column168: RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO LEAKING PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION DISCOVERED FULLY REGULATED UN1263 PAINT LEAKER. PACKAGE CONTAINED 2 - 1 GALLON CONTAINERS OF RED MARKING PAINT. BOTH WERE LEAKING FROM THE LID. THERE WAS NO CUSHION BETWEEN PAINT CANS. PACKAGE OFFERED USING SHIPPER NUMBER A42-06Y PUROLATOR 5995 AVEBURY RD MISSISSAUGA ON, CANADA L5R3T8.

AT 09:29 THE DRIVER NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING AND PLACED IT INSIDE A CLEAR PLASTIC BAG WITH PACKAGE # 1Z W4Y 581 84 4606 2373 WHICH WAS ALSO LEAKING. THE DRIVER FINISHED THEIR ROUTE AND RETURNED TO THE BUILDING WITH BOTH LEAKING UPS LAB PAKS STILL INSIDE THE PACKAGE CAR. SOMEHOW THE PLASTIC BAG WAS LOADED UNTO THE AIR BELT INSIDE A TOTE. WHEN IT REACHED THE AIR DOCK AT 19:44 THE PICK OFF MOVED THE TOTE OFF OF THE AIR BELT AND OPENED THE PLASTIC BAG ONLY TO REALIZE THAT THE LAB PAKS WERE LEAKING. THE PICK OFF INFORMENED THEIR SUPERVISOR WHO CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SITE, FOLLOWED BIOHAZARD PROCEDURES AND BROUGHT THE LAB PAK BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. THE URINE INSIDE THE PLASTIC COLLECTION CONTAINERS HAD FROZE DURING SHIPMENT CRACKING THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS.

column168: On 10/06/2017, at 2307 hours, personnel on CSXT Train H73206, while servicing an industry customer at Railroad Milepost BN 98.8, discovered GATX 62628, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, observed vapor emanating from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Tetra Technologies and the National Response Center were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report 2017-1006-1190#). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found two of four securement fastener bolts on the liquid line closure flange significantly corroded and releasing vapor due to an inadequate seal. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Robert Kline, phone 304-482-7655 Contractor personnel removed the two corroded fasteners and replaced all equipment in kind. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?    Cause Code:247  NARRI: 5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90

column168: ROSS EXPRESS DRIVER WAS DELIVERING TO CUSTOMER AND AS THE FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED AND BEING ACCOUNTED FOR THE DRIVER NOTICED ONE JUG HAD A SMALL HOLE IN IT FROM RUBBING FROM A NAIL IN SKID ON THE SAME WOODEN PALLET. ROUGHLY TWO GALLONS OF THE FIVE GALLON JUG HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR UNDER THE WOODEN PALLET THE FREIGHT WAS ON. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS VT TERMINAL DISPATCH AND WAS GIVEN HANDLING INSTRUCTION FROM THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK. THE DAMAGED JUG WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND THE HOLE WAS SEALED. THE CUSTOMER ACCEPTED THE DAMAGE JUG WITH THE OTHER 34 JUGS IN THE SHIPMENT. DRIVER THEN TOOK SOME EARTH TO COVER THE SPILL AND THEN THE CUSTOMER DISPOSED OF THE WASTE AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION.

column168: This was a release of the HazMat due to the shipper not fully tightening a cover on the discharge. Our driver did not observe any failure at the time of shipment nor following the package delivery at Terminal for temporary storage. Following loading of the IsoTank from temporary storage onto a chassis, another driver was conducting a pre-trip inspection when he observed a slow drip of hazardous material onto the chassis from the external cap of the discharge. Duration of the release is estimated at 52 hours. The release stopped after all of the HazMat trapped between the discharge valve and the cover had dripped out.     Our Reference No.: 66540

column168: At about 2100 hrs., when the Brewster Yard car inspector was inspecting an inbound train, he notice an odor coming from tank car UTLX 959651.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who then call Jeff Clapper, Superintendent of Motive Power to come out and investigate.  When Jeff investigated, he noticed that the A end liquid valve was iced up and leaking.  The valve handle was loose as was the valve plug.  Jeff tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  He then tightened the valve pug.  While working on the car, he noticed that the vapor valve was also leaking.  He tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  He then tightened the loose valve plug.  Both leaks were then stopped.  Seal number 1764479 was removed from the protective housing.  No new seal was installed.  The car was then released for service.    NARRI:  5(4+5)x(2)=90     Code:  115,117,379

column168: The trailer was observed to be dripping upon arrival at the Veolia ES Technical Solutions LLC facility located in West Carrollton, OH.  The trailer was placed in a containment dock and off-loaded once it was determined that it was safe to do so.  The leak was identified as coming from a 55 gallon drum with a pinhole at the bottom.  It appears that the customer, Sherwin Williams Auto Finishes attempted to patch the drum with adhesive putty.  The trailer was loaded by the customer so the Veolia driver did not see the condition of this drum prior to loading.
column169: The customer has been reminded that drums containing hazardous materials that are of poor integrity must never be offered for transportation.  Containers of poor integrity must be always be repacked or overpacked into a suitable DOT approved packaging.

column168: Drier noticed a leak at the connection from the hose to the trailer.. He immediately shut down the pump.. He disconnected the hose and noticed the gasket was leaking.. column168: Driver hooked up the product line but did not get a good "seal" because when he opened up the valve some product began to drip. He then re-positioned everything and had a good "seal" and began to unload. He was able to completed unload w/o any further issues. When he went to pick up the bucket, about 1 quart of product spilled out onto the asphalt. It immediately began to "foam up". column168: At approximately 1230 a Clean Harbors employee observed a liquid material under a van trailer that was staged in the 10 day area.  The liquid was leaking from the rear doors of the trailer and through the deck of the trailer.  Clean Harbors emergency personnel entered the van trailer a found a poly tote and the bottom valve was not secured and was leaking.  The valve was secured, the spill was contained and the van trailer was moved to a secondary containment area and was off loaded and the inside of the trailer was cleaned. The contaminated area was cleaned up using sorbent material and soil removal. The poly tote and clean up material was then sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Customers need to make sure all closures are properly closed and Clean Harbors driver's need to verify before loading them into trailers.

column168: On 10/12/17 at 1100 hours personnel in the CSXT Montgomery Yard discovered a load of Sodium Methylate Solution from tank car GATX26787 leaking product from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper Evonik Corp (Ottis, 251-591-8172) was notified.  Hepaco, CSX Hazmat Contractor, responded and found that the car was leaking from the thermometer well at the base where it screws into the pressure plate. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Evonik Corp (Ottis, 251-591-8172).  Hepaco checked the outage, the car had 7 inches of outage.  Hepaco conducted a partial offload and relieved the pressure on the car securing the release.  Evonik will be sending an MRU for repairs.        532 - Thermometer well valve seat    2(5+1+1) x (2+0) = 28 NARRI     Montgomery, AL – 10/12/17 – GATX26787 – Sodium Methylate Solution

column168: When the WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector was inspecting an inbound train, he found car GATX 204424 leaking from the top within the protective housing.  He was able to hear it from the ground and also smell it.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  When I arrived and investigated, I found that the B end liquid valve was not shut all the way and it was leaking through the valve plug which was loose.  I initially could not get the leak to stop by tightening the valve handle.  I had to work the valve open and closed several times to get it to seal.  I think it just had ice in the valve seat since the valve had ice formed on it.  I finally got the valve to seat and the leak stopped.  I tried to open and close the valve several times again to make sure that it was going to stay sealed and it did.  I then put sealant on the valve plug and tightened it.  I removed old seal 0209639 from the protective housing and installed new seal 971789 and then released the car for service.    NARRI: 5(4+5)x2=47       Code: 115,282

column168: Driver was traveling down the highway behind another vehicle when that vehicle abruptly stopped in front of him to make a left turn at an intersection.  The driver attempted to stop behind the vehicle but realized he could not do so he veered to the right of the vehicle onto the unimproved shoulder. While maneuvering to the right, the driver immediately tried to steer back to the left causing him to lose control and the weight of the cargo tank caused the truck to overturn onto it's right side.  The truck was traveling at an estimated speed of 23 mph when the vehicle initially began to roll-over.  Due to the truck overturning, product slowly leaked from a loose man way.  Approximately 30 gallons of methanol released from the compartment before emergency services could respond and extract the product from the tank.  The fire department and other emergency services were on scene and provided support while the vehicle was emptied and then uprighted back on it's wheels.  After the truck was removed from the scene, An Environmental contractor performed a site assessment and ensured no further action was needed.
column169: An investigation was completed on this accident and it was determined that the driver had slow reaction time to the truck abruptly stopping in front of him.  He also turned his steering wheel back to the left too aggressively after navigating around the vehicle in front of him which caused his truck to overturn.  This drive had been assigned remedial training to address these deficiencies.  This is the first accident this driver has had in over 20 years as a professional driver.

column168: A pallet with 4 x 700 lb drums of Phos acid 75% collapsed/ broke, causing the drums to shift and one drum to lean and rest part of the drum below the top level of the pallet. A fork lift was then used to try to stabilize the shifted/leaning drums and the fork punctured the drum at the bottom, spilling about 15 gallons (300 #) on the floor of the truck and onto the ground of the loading dock.  The puncture was about 6 inches long x 1 inch.  The spill lasted less than 10 minutes as the driver and customer were able to turn the drum on its side, raising the hole above liquid level in the drum stopping the spill. The hole was temporarily plugged and the drum was placed in an overpack/salvage drum. An absorbent berm was placed on the ground to stop the spread of the liquid. The spill was cleaned up with soda ash, lime and absorbent materials.
column169: To prevent recurrences stronger pallets are being used, improved banding procedures have been implemented, additional training on load securement has occurred, additional driver training regarding control of the delivery of his load will occur.

column168: On 10/20/17 at approximately 1:15 am an IMTT Field Operator was setting up a line displacement using the 96 dock line.  When he opened 7513 on the 96 dock line he noticed No.2 oil coming from a new flange on the new platform area at tank 7510. The IMTT Field Operator reported the incident to his supervisor and the IMTT Supervisor had him shut the tank immediately.  The incident was then reported to the IMTT Traffic who then called US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO) to respond to the area with a vacuum truck. The IMTT Supervisor contacted the IMTT Maintenance and was informed that a crew will be sent  to tighten up the flange.  The IMTT Operations Supervisor was able to get a box wrench off one of the IMTT Maintenance trucks and started to tighten the flange. The leak stopped and the IMTT Maintenance crew arrived to properly torque the flange.  The US Ecology vacuum truck recovered as much oil on the ground and adjacent storm water collection system as possible.  The IMTT Operations Supervisor was able to confirm that the collection system was shut down and would not be an environmental concern.  US Ecology also dispatched a clean up crew to the area later on during daylight hours.
column169: IMTT conducted a thorough investigation and determined that flange on a new platform area was loose.  It had been tagged to indicate it was properly torqued however upon interviewing the individual who was working on that project he indicated that he failed to confirm that he properly torqued the flange.  The individual was an employee of a contracted company hired by IMTT.  The contractor implemented a program to re-train all employees on the proper torqueing techniques before being allowed to continue working on similar projects at IMTT.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 10/20/2017, at 1111 hours, a Federal Railroad Administration Hazardous Materials Inspector in the CSXT Frontier Yard took exception to HOKX 112252, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, with the presence of historical and dried lading on top of the car. The inspector further identified the trailing three cars coupled to HOKX 112252 with similar dried lading indicative of a release from the reclosing external pressure relief device. It was determined HOKX 112252 was involved in a handling event inside the terminal that resulted in the reclosing pressure relief device to activate and release lading onto a total of 4 freight cars. Joseph Taylor, a CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager performed a visual inspection of the HOKX 112252 pressure relief device and discovered no evident external device defect and in the closed position. The Federal Railroad Administration informed Joseph Taylor the findings of the initial investigation of these freight cars indicated a rough handling and overspeed incident occurred resulting in the hazardous materials release. The car was isolated and Occidental Chemical Corporation, National Response Center, and New York State Department of Environmental Conservation were notified.  SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and removed all product from the exterior of the impacted freight cars. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mr. Gary Blasius of Occidental Chemical Corporation, phone 716-525-5839. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 700  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: When the Brewster Yard car Inspector was inspecting an inbound train, he noticed an odor coming from car PROX 36079.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who contacted Jeff Clapper, Supt. Of Motive Power to come out and investigate.  When Jeff arrived to the car he found that the vapor valve was leaking through the valve plug.  He tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  He then tightened the valve plug.  He also noticed the two liquid valve plugs were just hand tight.  He tightened those also.  The car was then released for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: When the FRA was doing a routine inspection in the WLE Brewster Yard, they found car CBTX 784464 leaking.  They were able to detect an odor.  They called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE to come out to investigate the car.  When I investigated, I found that the B end Liquid Valve was leaking vapor through the valve plug.  I tightened the loose valve handle and the leak stopped.  I checked the valve plug and it was loose.  I then tightened the valve plug.  There was no seal on the protective housing when I got on top the car.  The car was then released for service.          NARRI: 5(4+5)X 2 =47              Codes: 117

column168: While offloading a tanker, hauled by Dana Trucking, containing Exxsol D60 into Univar's storage tanks; an Univar employee accidentally started the offloading pump in reverse. This error caused material to be pulled from the storage tank thus backing up into the trailer.  Approximately 165 gallons of Exxsol D60 was released out of the top manway of the trailer before the pump was shut off. The Exxsol D60 released was completely contained in the sump underneath the unloading area, and was subsequently pumped into drums for disposal. Residual product on trailer was rinsed off, before advising driver and Dana Trucking's safety coordinator to proceed to a truck wash bay. Residual product on the offloading area surface was absorbed with Speedi-Dri and collected. No  product left secondary containment, and carrier was released in road-worthy condition.
column169: Proper offloading procedures were reviewed with the Univar employee.  We are also evaluating changes to the transfer pump switch signage and/or job aid used in the transfer process.

RECEIVED A CALL TO BOXLINE 8 , UPON MY ARRIVAL I DISCOVERED THE HAZMAT. I READ MY DECISION PERTAINING TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID WHILE WEARING MY PPE'S. LASTLY, RETURNING TO DMP WHERE THE FLAMMABLE WAS PROCESSED.

RESPONDER REQUESTED THAT A LEAKING PACKAGE BE PICKED UP; A 5 GALLON PAIL WAS NOTED TO HAVE A FLAMMABLE 3 DIAMOND LABEL. I RETRIEVED THE PACKAGE IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. NO REPORT OF EXPOSURE OR INJURY WAS NOTED BY THE SUPERVISOR.
PACKAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF USING UPS DMP AND ALL NECESSARY PPE

column168: On October 14, 2017, at 2139 hours personnel in the CSXT Radnor Yard reported CPDX 110010, a residue tank car which last contained Liquefied Petroleum Gas was suspected to be leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2017-1014-00102.  Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed the car was actively leaking from the pressure relief valve.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to consignee’s representative, Brian Thomas, with Chevron, at 832-854-5229.  Contractor personnel contained the release by the application of an emergency response capping kit.  The car was subsequently cleaned by flaring of the residual vapors and a nitrogen purge.  The car was held out of transportation pending a One Time Movement Approval from the FRA.     NAR Tank Car Cause Code: 422  NARRI: 2(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 36
column169: (NAR Tank Car Cause Code: 422)

column168: During a routine inspection of waste in ten-day storage, facility personnel discovered that some waste had leaked from the lower body of a drum onto the concrete floor in containment. No soil or water sources were impacted. A facility response crew was notified, and the area cordoned off. The response crew, wearing the correct personal protective equipment, determined this release, of 5 gallons,  was the result of a pin hole leak in the drum caused by interior corrosion. The leaking container was placed into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from cleaning the concrete floor. That salvage drum was correctly tightened to manufacturers specification and continued to its final destination without incident.     This release did not meet the minimal reporting requirements for the State of Ohio.
column169: No evidence of a release was present during the pickup and initial transportation of this drum. The generator of this waste stream was notified and asked to review the stream for the possibility of an off-spec condition. Also, the generator was asked to refresh its personnel on thorough container inspections prior to loading, with an emphasis on container integrity.

column168: United Pumping Service pumped out approximately 3,525 gallons of rinse-water from Lockheed Martin Plant 10, for transportation to Demenno Kerdoon (DK), Compton for for disposal.  It was manifested as Non-hazardous (contains rinsewater).  DK rejected the load for low pH 1.5.  The load was transferred on site to a stainless steel tanker truck and manifested as UN1760, Waste Corrosive Liquid, NOS (Hydrochloric Acid) 8, PG II, and returned to Lockheed Martin Plant 10.  No release occurred.
column169: This rinsewater waste was a compilation from five sources descaled with Rydlyme.  The pH analysis were taken using pH indicating strips, which produce "approximate" values.  The actual hydrochloric acid (HCL) concentration was low due to the fact that this was rinsewater that had completed its lyme descaling task.  The HCL was enough to cause a low PH measurement.  The generator is now aware to take a more accurate pH measurement of the rinsewater from the product Rydlyme.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: On October 11, 2017 at 0830 personnel in the CSXT West Springfield, Massachusetts Yard discovered ETCX623032 a loaded tank car of Ethyl Acetate leaking from around the manway. The car was isolated and Shipper, Solutia Inc., was notified via Chemtrec report 2017-1011-00056. CSX Hazmat, Solutia and RESCAR was dispatched to the scene and found the root cause to be from a misaligned manway. The manway was realigned properly and the tank was pressure tested to ensure no additional leakage would occur. The tank car was granted "One Time Movement Approval" by the Federal Railroad Administration and released for transport.     Cause Code: 208  2 x ( 5 + 3 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 32

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: During a routine site inspection, a roll off box staged at 10 day facility was found to have leaked; impacting soil only, no water ways or storm drains were in the vicinity.   An in house team donned proper personnel protective equipment and promptly remediated the area. Client was notified of free liquid found in container and subsequent release.  Free liquids were vacuumed off and soil was mixed thoroughly with absorbent material to solidify waste properly. A courtesy notification was made to the State of Utah Department of Environmental Quality to John Perry, who elected to not put it into the State system, due to it being under the reportable quantity threshold. The roll off box was transported to the disposal facility without further incident.
column169: Client was notified and advised to adjust procedures, adding in the use of binding agents or absorbent materials to ensure waste will not have any free liquids offered into transport. Driver was coached and retrained on the importance of completing a full container inspection, to include opening the lid, to ensure that the waste is acceptable for transportation, with every container offered into transportation.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Univar's driver was delivering sulfuric acid to our customer, he began by transferring via gravity to verify there were no issues or leaks. During this process it was noticed that the customer's valve had a small leak. Leaking acid was captured in a bucket and the driver stopped the delivery.     The load was rescheduled until after repairs were made. The repair was completed the following day and delivery was made two days later.

GRD PKG, UNDECLARED AEROSOLS DISCOVERED DURING DAMAGE PACKAGE INSPECTION.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED IN THE PRIMARY, SCANNED AND SPLIT TO THE SOUTH SORT AISLE. THE PACKAGE WAS WET AND THE SORTER SLIDE THE PACKAGE TO THE BOTTOM SLIDE. THE CLERK WORKING ON THE BOTTOM SLIDE MOVED THE PACKAGE TO THE REWRAP TABLE. THERE SHE NOTICED A STRONG ODER AND HER HANDS WERE EXPOSED TO THE WET SPOT. SHE NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER WORKING IN THE AREA. SHE THEN WENT TO WASH HER HANDS. THE RESPONDER PLACED THE PACKAGE INTO A DMP LINED SPILL CONTAINER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. IT WAS THERE, THE RESPONDER DISCOVERED, THAT THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS ACCOMPANIED BY AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT PRODUCT.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, SPARRED AND THEN SPLIT TO THE NORTH SORT AISLE. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN SORTED INTO THE BOXLINE. THE PRELOADER NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE OF LIQUID. HE THEN LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THEN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER THEN PLACED THE LEAKER INTO A LINED SPILL TUB. FOLLOWING THE DECONNAMINATION CHECK LIST THE RESPONDER CLEANED THE EQUIPMENT. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

On October 8, 2017, Fort Transfer Company notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3082, Surfonic L24-1, 9, PG III release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (349) 407 tanker trailer (3160) discovered a 1-quart release of product while at the Truck Stop. It is unknown in the cause of the release at this time. Contractor estimates that approximately 2 quarts of product has been released to the side of the tanker and asphalt. Contractor will use absorbents and portland cement to clean the release.  Contractor has finished initial cleanup activities. Contractor indicated that they have taped absorbent pads to the tanker as a precaution. Contractor believes that the released was caused due to the gasket of a washout cap. Contractor indicated that the gasket may be incompatible with the product. Contractors are onsite and confirm the leak is coming from a weld crack between the tanker shell and manifold, not the washout caps as previous thought.Contractors confirm the transfer is complete and they are getting ready to leave site. They combined the waste pads generated today with the waste in the original drum from the initial response.

APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT LEAKED INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE PARKING LOT BENEATH. SET ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO AN IMPERVIOUS SURFACE, AND DID NOT MIGRATE TO SURFACE SOILS OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. SET ENVIRONMENTAL UTILIZED A CITRUS BASED SOLVENT MATERIAL TO RECOVER ALL FREE PRODUCT, WHICH WAS CONTAINERIZED INTO AN OVER-PACK DRUM, ALONG WITH LEAKING DRUM, FOR DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: On 10/22/17 at approximately 12:24, yard crews reported a rotten egg odor near track 1430 in Barstow, CA railyard.  The area was isolated and BNSF Hazmat responders arrived to investigate the source of the odor.  Responders found the GATX 75567 to be leaking vapor with detectable vapor on a PID.  Upon closer inspection, responders identified the Vacuum Relief Valve as the source of the leak.  The VRV was removed and a plug inserted in its place.  The VRV was placed in a bag and secured within the multi valve housing cover for shipper handling and further inspection.  With the plug in place, the vapor dissipated and it was confirmed that there was no further release from the car.  The shipper obtained an OTMA 3 for the car and it continued to destination for unloading and further handling by the shipper/car owner.
column169: The shipper should ensure that all fittings on the car are in working order and leak free.  Review post loading practices and inspection procedures to help identify issues with VRV's.

column168: During a routine inspection of the 10 day storage by facility personnel, 4 bulging drums were found. Two of those bulging drums had ruptured their venting cap membrane, leading to a very small release of less than one ounce of waste, combined. These drums were in containment; no ground, soil, or water sources were impacted. An emergency response crew was summoned. Outfitted with the appropriate personal protective equipment, this crew safely relieved the pressure on all the affected drums, took analytical samples to determine the nature of the pressure build up. The generator was contacted, and a plan to chemically treat this waste was implemented. After the waste was fully stabilized, the bulging drums (including the ones which had leaked) were transferred to new drums of the appropriate UN specification. As of this writing, there is still one bulging drum with stabilized waste to be transferred into a fresh drum. The newly packaged drums have been shipped to their final destination without incident. The one remaining drum will be shipped to it's final destination soon.     This was initially reported and updated to the State of Connecticut DEEP Case #2017-5168.
column169: At the time these drums were initially transported, there was no sign of pressure buildup, bulging, or of a release from damaged drum vent diaphragms. This particular waste stream had been an issue in the past, which had caused CHES to suspend this waste stream until arrangements could be made with the generator to amend the manufacturing process that produced this waste, and to have the generator take additional steps to ensure this waste stream was stable through the temperature and vibrations of transit. This load was one of the first after re-accepting this waste profile. As a result of this continuing issue, CHES will no longer accept this waste stream into transit.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED AS ONE FIBERBOARD BOX WITH NO DANGEROUS GOODS LABELS OR MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX. THE CONTENTS WERE DESCRIBED IN THE MANIFEST AS “AIRCRAFT PARTS”.  THE SHIPMENT WAS OPENED IN THE NORMAL COURSE OF SCREENING CARGO AS REQUIRED BY TSA FOR INTERNATIONAL SHIPMENTS TRAVELING ON PASSENGER AIRCRAFT. THE CONTENTS WERE FOUND TO BE 20 LIFE VESTS EACH HAVING TWO 16GRAM CO2 CARTRIDGES. A CAT-6 QUALIFIED DG AGENT IDENTIFIED THE VESTS AS UN2990, LIFE SAVING APPLIANCES, SELF INFLATING WHICH IS LISTED IN THE IATA DANGEROUS GOODS REGULATIONS. THE SHIPMENT WAS REJECTED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.   UPON RETRIEVAL, THE SHIPPER INDICATED THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS ALLOWED UNDER PI-955 MAKING REFERENCE TO THE IATA DANGEROUS GOODS REGULATIONS. WHEN PACKING INSTRUCTION 955 WAS REVEIWED IT WAS FOUND TO APPLY TO LIFE SAVING APPLIANCES CONFIRMING THE IDENTIFICATION MADE EARLIER BY THE DG AGENT AND CONFIRMING THAT THE SHIPMENT REQUIRED A SHIPPERS DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS.
column169: THE CURRENT PROCEDURES ENABLED SCREENING PERSONNEL TO DISCOVER THE UNDECLARED DG AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PREVENTED FROM BEING LOADED ON AN AIRCRAFT. NO CHANGES TO THE PROCEDURES ARE NECESSARY.

column168: At 0955 hours on 10/24/17, an IMTT Field Operator called over the radio about a gasoline release at Pit 3S in Yard 5. The pump was being used to load the barge B-280 on Pier 1/W when he and another IMTT Field Operator noticed the release on their pump check. They immediatley shut down the pump from the sub station. The IMTT Emergency Response Team was called as well as IMTT Maintenance, Safety, and US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO).  The responders along with IMTT Maintenance dept. were able to stop the release which was coming from a broken nipple on a pressure relief line. The IMTT Maintenance dept. replaced the nipple and the IMTT Emergency Responders suppressed the vapors by laying a foam blanket down and diverting the flow gasoline to a collection point.
column169: A preliminary investigation determined that the nipple cracked off the discharge side of the Pit 3 south pump due to vibration and metal fatigue.  A Root Cause Analysis will be performed and Action Items assigned including changing the relief thread from schedule 80 to 160; perform a Pressure Cycle Fatigue Analysis on all similar reliefs; and a survey of all pump pad and relief piping.  All soil excavated during the clean up has been stockpiled and will be sampled for off site disposal.  All recovered product and fire water mixture has been temporarily stored in dedicated on-site tanks.

column168: On October, 8, 2017, Trimac-US notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3145, Alkyl Phenols, Liquid, N.O.S., 8, PG III release. According to the caller, the driver of the tractor (171030) 407 tanker trailer (470533) pulled into the Quality Inn Hotel and was doing an inspection of the unit and discovered that the tanker unit does not have a washout cap. Approximately 0.5 gallons of product has been released to the side of the tanker and the ground below. Upon contractor arrival, 4-gallons of product has been lost to 600' in length and 8' in width area of the asphalt parking lot. Contractor replaced the washout cap and pressure washed the impacted area. All waste water and absorbent materials were recovered and containerized into (9) 55-gallon metal drums. All waste was transported off site for disposal.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: SUBMITTED BY: SCOTT ARNDT ON 10/05/2017 AT 7:37:44 AM  ENVIRONMENTAL INCIDENT FORM SUBMITTED – STATUS CHANGED TO SUBMITTED    MODIFIED BY: SCOTT ARNDT ON 10/5/2017 AT 6:48:39 AM  ONCE THE DRIVER RETURNED TO HARCROS, AND WE WERE ABLE TO TAKE A LOOK IN THE TRAILER, IT WAS EVIDENT THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED. THE DAMAGED TOTE WAS SITTING AT A SKEWED ANGLE IN THE TRAILER, THE LOAD WERE SEVERELY BEND/DAMAGED.    THE CREW FROM ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, AFTER ENTERING THE TRAILER AND BEGINNING THEIR WORK, NOTED THAT SOME OF THE SPACER PALLETS WERE PARTIALLY CRUSHED, AND THAT MULTIPLE TOTES HAD MOVED.     AN EXAMINATION WAS MADED OF THE LOADING DOCK AND PAD WHERE THE LOAD ORIGINATED, AND THE DRIVE EXITING THE PROPERTY. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING PRODUCT.    MODIFIED BY: SCOTT ARNDT ON 10/3/2017 AT 6:58:49 PM  UPON TALKING WITH THE DRIVER, SHE DESCRIBED HAVING MADE A HARD STOP AT THE LAST LIGHT BEFORE TURNING ONTO THE FREEWAY (635 N) ON RAMP.      SHE SAID SHE WAS BRAKING AS SHE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION, THEN HER BRAKES GAVE WAY AND WERE NOT WORKING. A MOMENT LATER, THE BRAKES GRABBED, AND SHE WAS ABLE TO STOP THE VEHICLE.    SHE ALSO DESCRIBED USING THE JAKE BREAK WHILE RETURNING TO THE PLANT, FEARING THAT HER REGULAR BRAKES WOULDN’T WORK, OR MIGHT CREATE AN IGNITION SOURCE.    SUBMITTED BY: SCOTT ARNDT ON 10/3/2017 AT 5:24:55 PM  ENVIRONMENTAL INCIDENT FORM NOTIFICATION SENT

column168: While actively loading a tanker at the Veolia, Azusa, CA facility, the Veolia loader employee stepped away for few minutes. Upon return, he discovered that the liquid was coming over the top hatch & spilling to the secondary containment around the hatch. The Veolia loader immediately stopped the pump & closed the valve but by then approximately 30 gallons or less overflowed onto the ground.
column169: The Veolia Environmental Health and Safety Manager retrained the loader employees and reinforced the need to follow all the loading procedures including constant attendance. In addition, the incident was discussed extensively in the next safety meeting to raise awareness with the entire operations personnel group. All Veolia Loaders are required to carry a radio.  Emphasis was placed on the use of the radio to ask for help & not to hesitate get help from nearby available operation personnel.

AT 5:16 HOURS ON 10/08/2017, A SWITCHMAN IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) SHREVEPORT TERMINAL FOUND LOADED TANK CAR TILX110097 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE SWITCHMAN DETECTED FUGITIVE EMISSIONS FROM THE CAR AND WAS LATER TRANSPORTED TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM TO BE CHECKED OUT.  THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO EVALUATE AND SECURE THE TANK CAR, AND A SECOND CONTRACTOR TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING.  UPON EVALUATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE EMANATED FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS FOUND OPEN. THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR DECONTAMINATED. ONCE COMPLETE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO THE TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A ‘BULK’ SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILE AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECCURENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.  NAR:1006

column168: On October 13, 2017, TCNU 75074 was discovered leaking during transit in the Alliance, TX Intermodal facility. The material listed in the container was UN 1835 Tetramethylammonium Hydroxide, a class 8 corrosive. Upon opening the intermodal container, one (1) of the fifteen (15) IBC containers was found to be breached by blocking material at the front of the container. Approximately 50 gallons of liquid were lost from the IBC to the floor of the intermodal container and approximately two (2) gallons made it to the ground. The intermodal container was unloaded, cleaned and the liquid from the damaged IBC was transferred into poly drums for transport back to the shipper.
column169: Recommend review and revision of blocking and bracing procedures for a full load of IBC in a container. The material used failed to secure the load, more robust material should be used in the future.

column168: While preparing to load a trailer for transportation, a pallet staged in secondary containment at the facility’s 10 day storage site, was moved and subsequently a release was found beneath it. The release was not visible during routine facility inspections until the pallet was moved. Facility personnel, in proper personal protective equipment, immediately remediated the impacted concrete; no water ways or soil were present in the vicinity. An internal response team was dispatched to repack the container. The waste was shipped to its final destination without further incident.
column169: Facility advised client on a better method for preparing this waste stream for transportation, utilizing stacking techniques and adding absorbent material into box. Client was responsive to the advisement, but in an effort to ensure no release would happen again, they elected to start using 55 gallon drums instead of cubic yard boxes moving forward.

column168: At 0804 EST, ERTS received a call from Howard Sheppard Inc. regarding a cargo tank release. It was reported that due to experiencing issues with the dome lid on tanker #LT269, an estimated 75 gallons UN1830 released to the underlying asphalt and soil. Caller requested a team to respond to the site for cleanup and remedial activities. ERTS coordinated with Moran Environmental to respond to the site. Moran Environmental neutralized the site using baking soda outside on the area leading to the plant. They also applied Soda Ash and granular absorbents to the asphalt area outside the plant to remove remaining moisture from the parking area. ERTS has made all necessary regulatory notifications.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO BAY 458 IN THE AURORA CENTER. I ARRIVED IN FULL P.P.E. AND WAS SHOWN THE LEAKING BOX BEARING TWO DIAMOND LABELS. NONE OF THE EMPLOYEES GOT ANYTHING ON THEM. I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE FOR A CORROSIVE RESPONSE, SEEING AS IT WAS THE DOMINANT LABEL. AFTER TESTING THE MATERIAL WITH 5 INCHES OF PH TAPE. THE MATERIAL CAME UP AS 1. I THEN SPRINKLED SODIUM BICARBONATE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK TO NEUTRALIZE THE MATERIAL. AFTER THE MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED I SWEPT IT UP AND CONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL. THERE WERE SIX 2.5 LITER BOTTLES IN THE SHIPMENT. CLOSURES ON ONE BOTTLE FAILED CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ON ALL OTHER BOTTLES.
SUPERVISOR NOTICED PACKAGE COMING DOWN THE BELT AND THAT IT LOOKED BLEACHED FROM ACIDIC CONTENTS AND NOTIFIED RESPONDER TO TAKE CARE AND REMOVE FROM THE BELT.

column168: Veolia picked up the shipment on 10/25/17 at the 15800 Roscoe Blvd location and brought the shipment to Veolia's 10 day transfer location located at 107 S motor ave.  Upon arriving to Veolia's site, the drum was offloaded and transferred to a different trailer which was heading to the Veolia facility in Azusa, CA.  During this time, employees stated that there was no evidence or signs of a drum leaking.  The following morning around 6 AM, a Veolia driver was moving his tractor to hook up to the trailer when he noticed a spray pattern on his rear wheel.  He inspected the trailer and found that a drum was leaking.  The leaking drum was overpacked into a salvage drum.  The leaking drum had a pin hole leak at the bottom of the body (a little above the bottom chime).  There is also rust around the leaking area and was a contributing factor to the leak.
column169: Veolia employees have been retrained on container inspection and with emphasis placed on inspecting for rust spots that may compromise the integrity of the drum.

column168: While offloading a truck for the purposes of consolidating waste for delivery to a final destination, facility personnel noticed a drum appeared moist on its side surface near the bottom chime. Trained facility personnel in the appropriate level of personal protective equipment were called into to assess the drum; they found the drum had seeped slightly from an area with exterior corrosion near the bottom chime; the release was very slight, and only impacted the side skin of the drum. No pallets, equipment, floors, soil, or water were impacted. The drum was overpacked into a suitable UN specification rated salvage overpack drum and continued to its final destination without further incident.     This was reported to the CT DEEP, spill #2017-05429.
column169: The driver who placed this drum into transportation was given a written disciplinary warning, in addition to retraining on package inspection and closure, with an emphasis on inspection for drum integrity, corrosion, legibility of the UN specification markings.

column168: Event # 66684..     The driver arrived at the plant and pulled onto the scale and went inside to check in and have his paperwork checked.  One of the consignee employees smelled something and recognized it as the product in QC's trailer (Methyl Isobutyl Ketone). The tank was inspected and the cause of the release was thought to be a gap in the wash caps due to double gaskets.  The extra gasket was removed and the was cap tightened.      The product was then not able to be offloaded as the driver did not have a 2" disconnect fitting. The load was rescheduled for the following day.      The following day the product failed quality tests and was rejected the load.. Consignee employees had to blow the product out of their loading hose back into the trailer.. While doing this, it was noted that the vacuum release valve was leaking..     Unit taken to the shop and vacuum release valve was replaced..
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Event # 66700..     Driver arrived at plant to offload product..  Product failed quality tests and was rejected by consignee.. column168: During a routine load check while in transit, the driver noticed that a drum had a small release from the bottom chime. Only the floor of the box truck was impacted; no soil, water, or ground was affected. The driver and assistant donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and placed the drum in a salvage over-pack drum of the correct UN specification. The box truck floor was cleaned as well, and those waste materials placed in the salvage over-pack. The drum continued to its final destination without further incident.     This release did not meet the reporting requirements for the State of VT.

column168: Carrier driver arrived at consignee and was unloading product when hazmat was released.  A hazmat response team was mobilized to the site.  The source of the leak was a hose adapter connected to the bottom outlet.  The threads on this adapter were damaged due to crossthreading.  The adapter failed when the valve was opened to begin unloading, causing the adapter to disconnect from the bottom outlet.  The driver closed the valve and the release stopped.  The estimated duration of the release was two (2) minutes.  The tanker was taken offsite for repair.      Our Event #66541-1.

column169: Corrective action taken by the warehouse handling company :   a) Use only PALLETS (not containers) e.g. PMC’s / PAJ’s.  Build up allowed only on system isles or slave dollies  b) Do not load DGR on poor quality skids.  DGR must be within perimeter of the skid, not on the edge or over the perimeter  c) Ensure empty spaces between cargo is filled in with DGR/general cargo/plastic skids/form board/used pallet plastic –tightly rolled up  d) Use heavy duty boards / spreader boards after two layers of double stacked boxes/drums/cans for better stability of stacked cargo  e) Use shrink-wrap with DGR on skids as needed  f) Use green cherry nets as needed prior to netting  g) Ensure all DGR is secure when done with pallet netting; add additional straps as needed  h) Forking of the completed ULD is never allowed; transfer DGR ULD through the automated system or from the Slave dolly onto the automated system

column168: Carrier driver was pulled over by law enforcement and told that product was leaking from the top of the CTMV.  The driver observed that the washout cap was missing and noticed hazmat on the sides of the CMTV.  The shipper stated that the washout cap was installed after loading but was not checked for tightness.  The driver replaced the missing washout cap and a hazmat team was mobilized to the scene.  The duration of the release occured no longer than three hours.  The hazmat release ceased when the CTMV stopped.        Our Event #66739.

column42: BUTADIENES, STABILIZED OR BUTADIENES AND HYDROCARBON MIXTURE, STABILIZED CONTAINING MORE THAN 40% BUTADIENES
column168: AT 23:30 HRS ON 10/14/2017, AN ODOR WAS REPORTED COMING FROM A RESIDUE HAZMAT TANK CAR IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY(KCS) MOSSVILLE YARD LOCATED IN WESTLAKE , LA. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE CAR.   UPON ARRIVAL , IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR WAS EMANATING FROM SHQX 5203 (BUTADIENE, STABILIZED).  THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE A LOOSE VAPOR VALVE PLUG.  ADDITIONALLY,  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ALL PLUGS HAD INEFFECTIVELY APPLIED TEFLON TAPE.  THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR APPLIED TAPE TO THE PLUGS AND TIGHTENED ALL CLOSURES.  ONCE THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED , THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.   FILE NOTE:  ITEM 19- THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A "BULK" SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASE (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE.  FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASE (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. column168: On 10/25/17 at approximately 12PM one of our loaders was transferring the 4th and final load of spent acid from truck to railcar PROX 17136. These loads are transferred by pump. The railcar vent valve is connected to the truck trailer during this process and a small amount of pressure is built up in the car. The loader closed all the valves before disconnecting the hoses. He then removed the loading adaptor from the railcar siphon pipe before equalizing the pressure (These cars are not equipped with a siphon pipe valve) resulting in a spent acid release. There was minimal pressure in the car from the pump transfer, a different loader went up the railcar and opened the vent valve and the spill was stopped. The car spilled for approximately 30 seconds on to asphalt containment. We contacted Clean Harbors and they responded and cleaned the spill. I notified the National Response Center and the Oregon Emergency Response System of this incident.
column169: As a result of this incident we reviewed the transfer SOP focusing on disconnecting after transfers and the dangers of built up pressure. A new procedure has been written specifically for spent acid transfers which specifically targets this incident with a step by step system designed to prevent this and other possible failures. PT Railroad Services is a very small company of 8 employees and we take our commitment to safety very serious. We have safely handled transfers with out a lost time injury for 2,173 days. Through continued training and proper procedure we will prevent future incidents.

column168: During transit, a tractor hauling a tanker containing toluene rolled over due to unknown causes. Contractor absorbed standing product with absorbent pads and excavated a small area of impacted soil. Contractor placed pads and soil into a drum for disposal.
column169: Provide additional training to material handlers to ensure that they are implementing proper freight handling techniques and are able to recognize and prevent potential future incidents.

column168: AT 17:00 ON 10/5/2017, A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) TRAIN WAS SWITCHING CARS AT A KCS SIDING IN BENT OAK, MS. DURING THESE SWITCH MOVES, THE NDYX 814424, A LOADED HAZARDOUS WASTE HOPPER CAR, SIDE SWIPED ADMX15917, A LOADED NON-HAZMAT TANK CAR.   UPON IMPACT AND SEPARATION OF THE CARS, NDYX814424 RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 0.5 CUBIC YARDS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE LADING ONTO THE GROUND. THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED BACK INTO THE HOPPER CAR. A PATCH WAS WELDED OVER THE HOLE IN THE HOPPER CAR TO PREVENT THE CAR FROM LEAKING, MAKING IT A SIFT-PROOF PACKAGE CAPABLE OF SAFELY RETURNING TO TRANSPORTATION.   FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A BULK’ SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALVE.

column168: Two different vehicles were traveling in the opposite direction of our propane cargo tank vehicle. One of those vehicles stopped in the road and was rear-ended by the other vehicle. This pushed the stopped vehicle into our driver and to avoid a head-on collision, our driver swerved to the right but couldn't avoid contact with the vehicle. This caused our CTMV to over-turn on the roadway. The overturned vehicle began to leak liquid propane from a sheered off vapor return valve that connect the meter vapor eliminator to the cargo tank. Liquid was released through the excess flow valve that functioned properly and only leaked past the weep hole. This is a vapor valve in the cargo tank but it leaked liquid because the cargo tank was on its side. The local fire service controlled the leaking propane by using water fog patterns to dissipate the propane vapor. There was no physical damage to the cargo tank other than the lifting lugs being bent. Propane leaked an estimated 10-12 hrs. Propane liquid was removed from the overturned cargo tank except for approx. 300 gallons before the CTMV was uprighted. Once uprighted the remaining 300 gallons was removed and the vehicle was hauled away.
column169: I don't have any recommendations in this case as to how our driver could have avoided this accident. If he hadn't swerved to try and miss the oncoming vehicle, the driver of the other vehicle may have lost her life in a head-on collision.

column168: ON OCTOBER 17, 2017, VERDEGAAL BROTHERS YARD CREW WAS TRANSFERRING PHOSPHORIC ACID FROM A RAIL TANK CAR, # TGAX131413 TO A TRUCK TANKER, FOR OFF-SITE DELIVERY. LOCATION WAS ON VERDEGAAL BROTHERS, INC. PRIVATE RAIL SIDING. TRANSFER WAS WITH A THREE-INCH DIAMETER HOSE. THE AIR SPACE IN THE RAIL TANK CAR IS PRESSURIZED WITH AIR PRESSURE TO TRANSFER THE LIQUID PHOSPHORIC ACID. THE END OF THE HOSE FAILED NEXT TO THE FEMALE QUICK COUPLER ON THE END OF THE HOSE WHICH WAS ATTACHED TO THE TANK CAR FITTING. DURATION OF RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 15-20 MINUTES. AIR PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAR WAS 20 PSI.
column169: VERDEGAAL BROTHERS SIINCE UPGRADED THE TYPE OF TRANSFER HOSE USED, TO A HIGHER RATED STIFFER HOSE.   THE DESIGN OF THESE TANK CARS ARE FOR BOTTOM OFFLOADING. THE SWING HANDLE, WHEN UNCHAINED, SITS UNRESTRAINED.  AS IT HAPPENED IN THIS INCIDENT, THE TRANSFER HOSE WAS ATTACHED ON THE SAME SIDE OF THE RAIL TANK CARAS THE BOTTOM VAVLE HANDLE. WHEN THE THREE INCH HOSE RUPTURED, IT PUSHED THE RAIL TANK CAR VALVE HANDLE OUT OF THE RETAINING PIPE AND THE VALVE HANDLE FELL TO THE GROUND, IN A PUDDLE OF RELEASED PHOSPHORIC ACID. IT WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN SAFE FOR A PERSON TO RETRIEVE THE VALVE HANDLE IN A PUDDLE AT THE SAME TIME AS THE RELEASE. A SUGGESTION IS TO EXAMINE THE DESIGN OF THE HANDLE OF THE TANK CAR.  VERDEGGAL BROTHERS, INC. HAS MADE A POLICY CHANGE, TO ALWAYS POSITION THE TRUCK TANKER ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR WHERE THE VALVE IS LOCATED. THE TANK CAR WILL BE POSITIONED ON THE RAIL SIDING SO THIS CAN BE DONE. THIS WAY, THE OPERATOR CAN IMMEDIATELY GO TO THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR AND CLOSE THE VALVE.   VERDEGGAL BROTHERS IS MODIFYING THE BOTTOM MAINFOLD FITTINS A METAL PIPE MANIFOLD IS BEING MODIFIED SO THERE WILL BE AN ADDITIONAL THREE-INCH VALVE NEXT TO THE MALE THREE-INCH QUICK COUPLER ON THE RAIL CAR WHEN OFF-LOADING.

column168: During the offload of American Airlines Flight 1318 SJC-DFW at DFW gate A13 the bag started smoking. Gate crew quickly removed bag from the aircraft and placed it on the ground. They then called for Management. The Customer Service Manager called for an Environmental Coordinator and a GSC was also involved.    Discovered in the bag was a broken open package of "Snap Bangers, Red Cracker Snaps" Explosive Fireworks Snaps. The passenger continued to Tulsa, Oklahoma with one bag.  The bag involved in the Hazmat Incident was held at DFW for FAA Inspection.  FAA Hazmat PHI and local FAA Hazmat Inspector were both notified of the incident.
column169: Educating the general public on Hazardous Materials and the risks of introducing them into air transport.

column168: THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS OPERATOR ERROR. THE DRIVER WAS FILLING WHEN THE TANK BECAME OVERFILLED CAUSING DIESEL TO SPILL OUT AROUND THE FITTING. THE DRIVER HAD NEGLECTED TO STICK THE TANK TO ENSURE THE FULL REQUESTED LOAD WOULD FIT. ALL EQUIPMENT WAS IN FUNCTIONING CONDITION AND DID NOT CONTRIBUTE TO THE INCIDENT. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY AROUND A MINUTE, AS SOON AS THE DIESEL BEGAN TO SPILL OUT AROUND THE FITTING THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PUMP STOPPING THE FLOW AND LIMITING THE RELEASE TO APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN GALLONS. THE RELEASE WAS ABLE TO BE MANAGED BY USING THE ON-BOARD SPILL KIT OF THE TRUCK, THE SPILL DID MANAGE TO REACH AN ON-SITE CATCH BASIN THAT WOULD LATER BE PUMPED OUT BY NRC.
column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER WENT THROUGH “STICK-THE-TANK” REFRESHER TRAINING. ALL DRIVERS WERE ALSO REMINDED OF THE IMPORTANCE OF STICKING THE TANK RATHER THAN RELYING ON INFORMATION FROM DISPATCH. A TRAINING REFRESHER PROGRAM AND OPEN DISCUSSION HUDDLES ARE GREAT TOOLS TO DECREASE THE FREQUENCY OF RECURRENCE.

column168: Our driver was headed to Camden BP from the terminal in Indy. It was a new route for this driver. His GPS took him on a backroads route. Mike came up to a steep railroad track/embankment but thought he could clear it successfully. When he crossed the tracks his dolly legs struck the track. The legs were forced up and ruptured compartment #2 that had 1500 gallons of UL E87. The hole was approximately 2" in diameter in the bottom of the compartment.(About the size of a quarter). The fuel didn't start to come out of the compartment until he got a few hundred yards down the road. Mike drove about another quarter mile before realizing something was wrong. He stopped and saw his trailer was leaking fuel out. Mike then called Dispatch. Lykins notified local emergency services. Liberty Fire Department was first on the scene. The Safety Dept. was notified and made all necessary reports. Then headed to the scene where the environmental company (SES), local sheriff and IDEM met up with Lykins Safety Department. Liberty Fire and Rescue was able to slow the leak and Union County Co-Op pumped out the gas from the compartment and delivered it to Camden BP. SES proceeded to clean up the gas that was spilled according to the requirements by IDEM.
column169: We have advised our drivers that if they have a new location to deliver to, to verify with dispatch on an appropriate route to take. At our last round of safety meetings we clarified spill reporting and mitigation procedures.

column168: ON OCTOBER 20, 2017 A FUEL TANKER TRUCK OVERTURNED AND DISCHARGED A MIXTURE OF GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL (3,588 GALLONS) TO A SURFACE WATER BODY ADJACENT TO THE SOUTH OF THE OVERSEAS HIGHWAY. ABSORBENT PADS WERE DEPLOYED AND REMOVED ON OCTOBER 23, 2017. ADDITIONAL PADS WERE THEN PLACED AND REMOVED ON OCTOBER 27, 2017. ALSO ON OCTOBER 27 2017, PRODUCT AND SHEEN WERE SKIMMED FROM THE SPILL AFFECTED MANGROVE AREA UTILIZING A VACUUM TRUCK. A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 850 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM "SHEEN" AND CONTACT WATER WAS RECOVERED FROM THE SPILL AREA. SOIL AND SURFACE WATER SAMPLES WERE SUBSEQUENTLY COLLECTED AT THE SITE ON NOVEMBER 7, 2017. THE SAMPLES WERE ANALYZED FOR VOLATILE ORGANIC COMPOUNDS (VOCS) BY EPA METHOD 8260, POLYNUCLEAR AROMATIC HYDROCARBONS (PAHS) BY EPA METHOD 8270 AND TOTAL RECOVERABLE PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS (TRPH) BY THE FL-PRO METHOD. ALL SAMPLES WERE WITHIN THE FDEP CLEANUP TARGET LEVELS (CTLS). A SOURCE REMOVAL REPORT HAS BEEN SUBMITTED TO THE FDEP.
column169: THE ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY THE ACTIONS OF THE OTHER VEHICLE.

column168: The driver of the tractor-trailer crested the top of a bridge and suddenly seen that traffic was stopped and trying to avoid hitting a disabled vehicle in the roadway. He immediately applied his brakes but was unable to avoid contact with two other vehicles.  One vehicle impacted the bulk liquid tanker.  The impact to the trailer damaged a temperature gauge and resulted in product being released onto the roadway.  The Port Arthur fire department responded and applied a sealing putty to the tanker to minimize the release and oil booms to contain the spill.  The product was transferred out of the damaged tanker.  Once the damaged tanker was removed from the scene, SWS Environmental Services began a clean-up of the scene.  They utilized absorbent pads, absorbent booms and floor dry to clean-up the spill.  No product was released onto the soil or any waterways.
column169: This bridge does not have any shoulder available for disabled vehicles and is of an older construction with a very steep grade.  The steep grade does not allow visibility of issues with traffic until after you crest the bridge.  This lack of a shoulder and reduced visibility were significant contributors to this accident.

column168: TANK #1 (20,000 GALLON) AND TANK #2 (15,000 GALLON) ARE TWO SEPARATE PARTS OF A SINGLE TANK STRUCTURE THAT HAS A COMBINED HOT LIQUID ASPHALT STORAGE CAPACITY OF 35,000 GALLONS. WHILE THE MIX PLANT CREW WAS UNLOADING A TANKER OF LIQUID OF ASPHALT INTO THE ONSITE ASPHALT CONCRETE STORAGE TANK #2, THE TANK BECAME OVERFULL AND APPROXIMATELY 30-50 GALLONS OF LIQUID ASPHALT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK'S OVERFLOW PIPE. THE OVERFLOW PIPE IS DESIGNED TO RELEASE LIQUID ASPHALT TO A SAFE AREA ON THE SIDE OF THE FACILITIES STORAGE TANKS THAT IS CLOSE TO THE GROUND (SEE BELOW PHOTOGRAPHS).    ROOT CAUSES OF THE INCIDENT INCLUDE:  THE LIQUID LEVEL OF AC TANK #2 WAS NOT VERIFIED BEFORE UNLOADING BEGAN.  THE MIX PLANT PERSONNEL DID NOT COMMUNICATE WITH EACH OTHER REGARDING THE ESTABLISHED PROCEDURES FOR UNLOADING OF THE HOT LIQUID ASPHALT.
column169: REVIEW AND RETRAINED AN ASPHALT UNLOADING PROCEDURES. (SEE ATTACHED JOB SAFETY ANALYSIS (JSA))

column168: AA Flight 272 MSP-PHX diverted into LNK due to a medical emergency.  Two walk-around oxygen cylinders had been used by the Flight Attendants during the emergency.  Upon landing in LNK, the cylinders needed to be replaced to make the aircraft airworthy.  Two replacement cylinders were ferried from ORD to LNK.  An AA Aircraft Mechanic was on-board Flight 272 and volunteered to replace the oxygen cylinders in the cabin.  After completion of the work, the Aircraft Mechanic, Captain of the ferry aircraft or ground personnel with the FBO in LNK inadvertently loaded the used cylinders into the cargo compartment of the ferry aircraft for return to ORD.  One cylinder was completely empty.  However, the other used cylinder had approximately 250 PSI of oxygen remaining.  The cylinders were placed back in the American Airlines owned DOT31FP compliant boxes but not declared as required and not reported to the Captain via NOTOC as required.  The packages were discovered by American Airlines Stores personnel after they had been offloaded from the returning ferry aircraft as which time they reported the discrepancy to management.
column169: Better training of Aircraft Mechanics and Flight Crew to understand that these are hazmat parts that cannot fly unless all regulatory requirements have been satisfied.  Even though both understood that one cylinder was empty, the other more than half depleted and the location of where they were loaded does not relieve them or the company of compliance with the regulations. Efforts are underway to ensure better training of both work groups regarding off-line instances such as this.

column168: On 10/07/2017, in the Roseville, CA UPRR rail yard, PLMX 137292 was reported to have an odor coming from it. During the response an audible release was noticed at ground level. column168: UTLX 46511 was reported having a chemical odor around it.  Upon inspection of the car an odor was found around the bottom outlet valve.  The BOV cap was removed and found to be full of liquid, corrosion, and the gasket worn.  Further inspection on the top of the car found a vapor release coming from the liquid line eduction tube flange. The gasket was misaligned and compressed. The liquid line valve and eduction tube were removed as a result of a broken stud.  A new stud was installed with a  new gasket and blind flange stopping the release and securing the car.

All impacted debris and the damaged drum was properly containerized and staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

On October 24, 2017 during unloading operations, terminal personnel accidentally punctured a (1) 55-gallon steel drum containing UN1866 Resin Solution "Viking Maya LT Blue Shimmer" during a forklift accident. Approximately 2-gallon released to the concrete dock floor. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release by utilizing granular absorbents.

column168: Approximately 15 gallons of UN1197, non- regulated Terpen Hydrocarbons, NOS (TERPENES), Class 3, III, released from a 55 gallon metal drum that appeared to be punctured by a forklift blade. The release impacted the trailer floor.

Tank car TILX302263 was discovered leaking by a FRA Inspector.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the leak was found to be coming from a liquid line valve.  The leak was the result of the valve being partially open and the closure plug not properly secured.

During offload, leak observed from the bonnet gasket on the 2” offload valve. Driver stated they already tried tightening the bolts but the gasket continued to leak.  The unloading process was stopped and the line was cleared.  The cargo tank was depressurized utilizing the location vent system and water hose for vapor mitigation.  Once vapor pressure was below 20 psi, the cargo tank returned to Honeywell plant for investigation and repair.  Release amount was estimated at  less than 1 lb.
column169: The valve was determined to have leaked at the stem packing.  A precautionary retorque (both bonnet and stem) of all trailers with this type valve was immediately initiated before its next shipment.A 30 day re-torque program has also been initiated.
